gd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1446–1503":"1446–1503","1450–Female":"1450–Deceased","1480–1541":"1480–1541","1392–Male":"1392–Deceased","1394–1434":"1394–1434","1503":"1503","1414":"1414","1446":"1446","1434":"1434","1541":"1541","1450":"1450","1471":"1471","1394":"1394","1480":"1480","1392":"1392","St Mich On Wyre, Lancashire, , England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Halewood, Metropolitan Borough of Knowsley, Merseyside, England":"Halewood, Merseyside, England, United Kingdom","LATHOM, Lancashire, , England":"Lathom, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Halewood, Lancashire, England":"Halewood, Lancashire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Rawcliffe,St Mich On Wyre,Lancashire,England":"Rawcliffe, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Irelande","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: ethnic name denoting someone from Ireland, from Middle English <i>Irland</i>, <i>Irlond</i>, <i>Erlond</i> (Old English <i>Īraland</i>). The country gets its name from the genitive case of Old English <i>Īras</i> ‘Irishmen’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’. The stem <i>Īr-</i> is taken from the Celtic name for Ireland, <i>Èriu</i>, earlier <i>Everiu</i>. The Latin name was <i>(H)ibernia</i>. The surname is especially common in Liverpool, England, which has a large Irish population. Compare   Irish  .","Americanized form of   Erland  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Irelan","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Ireland  ."]},{"name":"Irland","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Ireland  ."]},{"name":"Irish","meanings":["English and Irish (Kilkenny): ethnic name for someone of Irish origin, from Old French <i>Ireis</i> or Middle English <i>Irish</i> ‘Irish’, Latinized as <i>Hiberniens(is)</i>. Compare   Ireland  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Irelande was born in 1446, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Adam Ireland, was 54 and his mother, Margaret Stanley, was 52. He married Clemence Kirkby in 1471, in Rawcliffe, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1503, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 57, and was buried in Halewood, Merseyside, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1446–1503":"1446–1503","1450–Female":"1450–Surnud","1480–1541":"1480–1541","1392–Male":"1392–Surnud","1394–1434":"1394–1434","1503":"1503","1414":"1414","1446":"1446","1434":"1434","1541":"1541","1450":"1450","1471":"1471","1394":"1394","1480":"1480","1392":"1392","St Mich On Wyre, Lancashire, , England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Halewood, Metropolitan Borough of Knowsley, Merseyside, England":"Halewood, Merseyside, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","LATHOM, Lancashire, , England":"Lathom, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Halewood, Lancashire, England":"Halewood, Lancashire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rawcliffe,St Mich On Wyre,Lancashire,England":"Rawcliffe, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1446–1503":"1446–1503","1450–Female":"1450–Kuollut","1480–1541":"1480–1541","1392–Male":"1392–Kuollut","1394–1434":"1394–1434","1503":"1503","1414":"1414","1446":"1446","1434":"1434",